            <div type="translation">
            <p>Front: (Here lies) in peace and blessing mother Helene, a Jewess, who loved the
                    orphans. (She lived for) about sixty years and compassion and blessing were the
                    path on which she walked.</p>
                <p> Back: In peace and blessing.</p>
            </div>

            <div type="commentary">
                <p>An irregular slab of polished limestone, broken in two pieces down
                    the middle and chipped at the upper right corner, with lines of
                    ordination and traces of red paint inside the letters, although it
                    is unclear if the paint is modern or ancient. The back side is
                    polished with two lines of crudely inscribed text.</p>
                <p>The text records an epitaph of a Jewish woman named Helene, which commemorates her
                    care for orphans. Her identity and social status are unknown.</p>
                <p>line 2: Helene is titled Ἄμα, a title that is usually given to Christian holy women and monastics, but
                    is more likely an alternative spelling of ἄμμα or ἄμμας, which means
                    “nurse”, “mother” or “foster mother.” This explanation is most probable as the
                    epitaph describes a relationship with orphans, for whom Helene could have served
                    the role of foster mother or guardian.</p>
                <p>line 3: Helene is described as “having loved the
                    orphans” (ἀγαποῦσα τοὺς ὀρφανούς). Orphans are usually mentioned in epitaphs in
                    the contexts of their parents’ death, or as threats towards grave-robbers. The
                    references to a relationship between orphans and a woman who is not their kin is
                    therefore unique. The verb ἀγαπάω does appear in Jewish epitaphs, but nowhere else in the context of
                    caring for orphans. This might imply that Helene’s care for the orphans was a
                    voluntary act of charity.</p></div>
            

